comment.body:
@gadoofou87 Thank you very much for the cpu_features shared-lib fix! This had held me up making progress on #624 

Regarding the question how to integrate `cpu_features`, I usually also like stuff that "just works", but this statement from [the link quoted above](https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/README.md#incorporating-into-an-existing-cmake-project ) makes me uneasy in this case as we want to ensure our system works (builds/runs) smoothly on all platforms (incl. Windows):

> This has the significant advantage that the same compiler and linker settings are used between gtest and the rest of your project, so issues associated with using incompatible libraries (eg debug/release), etc. are avoided. This is particularly useful on Windows

--> How certain are you that `ExternalProject_Add` has no negative aspects in our case, incl. Windows (with which I have very little experience)?

@xvzcf : At first glance, _I_ don't see any drawbacks as --unlike `gtest` users in the case quoted above-- we don't need to share build parameters with cpu_features from liboqs, so what'd you say: If it works (all build checks pass again) on all platforms, what about giving the `ExternalProject_Add` integration a go?  As `cpu_features` sure looks like a live project with updates/fixes coming online, a "dynamic" integration (either via `ExternalProject_Add` or git subproject) benefits OQS. The stuff I read about [git subproject integration](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Submodules) makes me think that that approach would be too cumbersome for us.

